                  </hi>. I am shopman to Mr. Henry Joseph Niblett, a sil<lb></lb>versmith and pawnbroker, in Farringdon-street On the evening of the 27th of December I was in the shop, and saw the prisoner about half-past seven o'clock, as I was engaged serving a customer—I observed the pri<lb></lb>soner come and take a hat off a peg—he ran off across the road—I pur<lb></lb>sued and took him with the hat in his possession—he made a desperate resistance, and tried to get away, but I succeeded in keeping him—he did not strike me, but tried to get from my grasp—this is my master's hat.</p>
